	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Namibia: 'Catch the consumer, not the fish'</h1>

			
			<h4>
												31 March 2005
										</h4>

					</header>


				<div class="intro">

						<p> The Namibian minister for fisheries and marine resources told a meeting of 300 industry captains on April 14th 2005 that it was up to them to steer the sector out of trouble. He was reacting to a recent submission by the industry urging the cancellation of catch-quota levies, a rebate on fuel prices and lower port-usage fees.</p>

		</div>
		
		
					<p> Earlier, on March 24th 2005, the Namibia Economic Society had held a panel discussion on the current dire state of the fishing industry and concluded that the objective for the sector should be 'catch the consumer, not the fish &quot;The industry needs to look at value share of their companies rather than product share in the export markets &quot;Companies must work as a team under a cluster system that emphasises product development, market research, and competitiveness in the globalised world', according to the NES president. During the discussion, the Confederation of Namibian Fishing Associations presented a report reviewing the specific challenges faced by the fishing industry, highlighting the fact that many factors beyond the control of the industry had contributed to a situation in which it was exceptionally hard to operate profitably. However, difficulties are also due to the way the sector operates: 'Too many concessionaries holding fish quotas fragment the industry, and the playing field between <i>bona fide</i> Namibian companies and foreigners who own Namibian companies, is not levelled'.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>
<a href="http://www.namibian.com.na/2005/April/national/05A709D78B.html" target="_self">Press article 'Namibian fishing industry: an overview', <i>The Namibian<...</a> </p><p>
<a href="http://www.namibian.com.na/2005/March/national/05A215B444.html" target="_self">Press article '2005 to be toughest year yet for fishing industry', <i>Th...</a> </p><p>

<a href="http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/IRIN/d1d974651e11770304a32529f19cbd8f.htm" target="_self">Press article ' Namibia: fishing industry on the line', Reuters <i>Alert...</a> <br/> </p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p> External factors, beyond the control of the Namibian fish-exporting sector (as for other ACP countries) certainly affect the profitability of the sector. However, it is clear that the structure of the Namibian sector and the way access rights to resources have been established is also a cause of difficulties.</p><p> The objectives of Namibian fisheries policy in the last decade have been towards the Namibianisation of the industry and the establishment of sustainable levels of exploitation. Foreign operators, including Europeans, were offered incentives to create joint ventures with local Namibian partners, the idea being that the more shares there are of the cake, the greater is the number of people who benefit from it. But with this form of Namibianisation, based on the transfer of an industrial model of fisheries development with high running costs, there is a limit to how far access to the resources can be shared. With too many quota holders it is structurally impossible for several of the holders to operate profitably, given that their slice of the quota cake is too small. In such a context, external factors that increase costs (such as the rising price of fuel) can quickly undermine the financial viability of the fishing company. Any deterioration in the state of stocks would also have adverse impacts on such fragile companies, built on resource-access shares too small to be viable. Therefore, the motto 'catch the consumer, not the fish' can make the difference between bankruptcy and survival. In order to survive, those companies with a limited access to resources need to invest in the research and development of new products and new markets that can attract value added for the Namibians. But such investment needs support, especially when companies are having to operate on small margins.</p>
		</div>
		
		<div class="clear"></div>

		
